  "prompt": "How much did it cost to build Walt Disney World?",
  "response": "Walt Disney World Resort, located near Orlando, Florida, was initially built with an estimated investment of **approximately $400 million**. This figure covers the development and construction phases that led to its grand opening on October 1, 1971. \n\n**Inflation Adjustment:**\nTo put this into perspective with today's dollars, adjusting for inflation from the early 1970s to 2023, the $400 million investment would be roughly equivalent to **over $2.5 billion**. This substantial investment reflects the scale and ambition of Disney's vision for a comprehensive entertainment complex featuring theme parks, hotels, and other attractions.\n\n**Subsequent Investments:**\nIt's important to note that the initial cost was just the beginning. Over the decades, Walt Disney World has undergone numerous expansions and additions, including the introduction of new theme parks like Disney's Hollywood Studios and Epcot (originally the Experimental Prototype Community of Tomorrow), as well as multiple resorts, water parks, and other facilities. Each of these expansions has added to the total investment, making Walt Disney World one of the most significant and continuously evolving entertainment destinations in the world.\n\n**Funding Sources:**\nThe project's funding was a combination of corporate financing, investments, and strategic partnerships. Walt Disney himself played a pivotal role in securing the necessary funds, including selling stock in the company to raise capital for the venture. This strategic financial planning was crucial in bringing the sprawling resort to life.\n\nIn summary, the initial construction of Walt Disney World cost around $400 million in the early 1970s, which translates to over $2.5 billion today when adjusted for inflation. Continuous investments over the years have further expanded and enhanced the resort, solidifying its status as a premier global entertainment destination.",
